In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims April 2nd as World Autism Awareness Day. He recognizes the millions of people living with autism spectrum disorder, including 1 out of every 68 American children. The President emphasizes that Americans with autism contribute to society and should be supported. He mentions that the Affordable Care Act ensures that people with autism cannot be denied coverage, and preventive services, including autism and developmental screenings, must be covered at no cost to parents. The President also expresses the commitment to eliminate discrimination against students with autism and provide schools with resources to help them succeed. He highlights the importance of investing in research, early detection, and support services for individuals with autism. Additionally, President Obama mentions the Brain Research through Advancing Innovative Neurotechnologies (BRAIN) Initiative, which aims to enhance understanding of the human mind and potentially lead to advancements in autism science. The President concludes by urging all Americans to learn more about autism and support individuals on the autism spectrum and their families.